w5c: Fitting AR(p)

Nao Mimoto - Dept. of Statistics : The University of Akron


Class Web Page



1. De-mean or Not

Theoretically, AR(\(1\)) has mean of 0. \[ X_t = \phi X_{t-1} + e_t \hspace10mm e_t \sim WN(0,\sigma^2). \] If the observed series looks like AR(\(1\)) with constant mean, our model is \[ Y_t = \mu + X_t, \hspace10mm \mbox{ where } \mu \mbox{ is a constant and $X_t$ is AR(p).} \] That means, \(Y_t\) has a mean of \(\mu\), and we need to de-mean (de-trend) by letting \[ \hat X_t = Y_t - \hat \mu = Y_t - \bar Y. \] before modeling \(\hat X_t\) with zero-mean AR(\(1\)).

include.mean=TRUE is default in Arima() of forecast package.

If you use include.mean=FALSE option, that means our model is \[ Y_t = X_t. \] and \(Y_t\) is believed to have mean of \(0\). \(Y_t\) is directly being modeled with zero-mean AR(p) model.

Ex: De-mean or not

  set.seed(3563)
  Y    <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, .3) ), 100 )  + 8.5
  plot(Y, type="o")

  mean(Y)
## [1] 8.11923
  library(forecast)              # install.packages("forecast") if you haven't

  Fit01 <- Arima(Y, order=c(2,0,0))                             # fit AR(2) to Y

  Fit02 <- Arima(Y, order=c(2,0,0), include.mean=FALSE)         # don't de-mean

  Fit03 <- Arima(Y-mean(Y), order=c(2,0,0), include.mean=FALSE) # de-mean by hand

Fit01 is fitting AR(2) with mean using MLE.

Fit02 is fitting AR(2) with zero-mean using MLE.

Fit03 is fitting AR(2) with zero-mean after you demean by hand.

2. Order Selection of AR(p)


a. ACF and PACF

ACF of AR(p) tails off PACF of AR(P) cuts off at lag \(p\). *Theoretical value of PACF(\(h\)) are \(\phi_h\).

  plot(Y, type="o")

  layout(matrix(1:2, 1, 2))  # two plots side by side
  acf(Y)                     # plot sample ACF
  pacf(Y)                    # plot sample PACF

  layout(1)                  # return to 1 plot layout


b. AIC and log-likelihood

*Likelihood function \[ L(\theta) = f(X_1) \, f(X_2) \, \cdots f(X_n) \]

*Akaike Information Criteria: \[ \mbox{AIC} = -2 \, \log(\mbox{maximum likelihood}) + 2 k \] \(k=p+1\) if non-zero mean is included in the model, and \(k=p\) if not.

*Choose \(p\) that MINIMIZE AIC.

*The auto.arima() in forecast package chooses \(p\) value based on AIC automatically.

Ex: AIC Simulation Study

If we use AIC all the time, what is the probability we end up with correct \(p\)?

Set \(p=2\). Generate simulated AR(2). Use auto.arima(Y) and search for best \(p\) by using Minimum AIC. *Repeat 1000 times. How many time do we end up with right \(p\)?

  #- Simulation Study of choosing p by AIC
  Result <- 0
  for (i in 1:1000){
    Y    <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, .3) ), 100 )  + 8.5
    Fit7 <- auto.arima(Y, d=0, max.q=0)        # find AR(p) by AIC
    Result[i] <- length(Fit7$model$phi)        # save value of p chosen
  }
  head(Result, 100)                       # first 100 p
##   [1] 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 1 2 2 2 2 1 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 1 2 2 5 2 2 2 2 2 1 2 2
##  [40] 2 2 1 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 1 2 2 2 2 2 5 2 2 2 2 2 1 2 2 3 2 2 2 2 2 3
##  [79] 2 1 3 1 2 2 1 2 2 3 2 2 1 1 3 2 4 2 2 1 2 2
  mean(Result==2)                         # propotion of times p=2
## [1] 0.786


c. Parameter Significance

After \(p\) was suggested by AIC, test the pameter estimate for significance using large-sample 95% CI. i.e. \(\hat p \pm 2 SE\) If the last parameter is not significant, reduce \(p\) by 1, and fit again.

Ex: When AIC fails

If we use AIC all the time, what is the probability we end up with correct \(p\)?

Set \(p=2\). Generate simulated AR(2). Use ar(Y) and search for best \(p\) by using Minimum AIC. *Repeat 1000 times. How many time do we end up with right \(p\)?

  #- Choosing p by AIC, stop if p > 2
  Result <- 0
  for (i in 1:1000){
    Y    <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, .3) ), 100 )  + 8.5
    Fit7 <- auto.arima(Y, d=0, max.q=0)        # find AR(p) by AIC
    Result[i] <- length(Fit7$model$phi)        # save value of p chosen
    if (Result[i] > 2){
      print( length(Fit7$model$phi) )
      break
    }
  }

3. Residual Analysis of AR(p)

After parameter estimation, say we have AR(2) model \[ X_t = \hat \phi_1 X_{t-1} + \hat \phi_2 X_{t-2} + e_t. \] \(X_t\) are observations. We never get to observe \(e_t\).

We must estimate \(e_t\) by residuals. \[ \hat e_t = X_t -\hat \phi_1 X_{t-1} -\hat \phi_2 X_{t-2} \hspace10mm t= 3,4,\ldots,n \] This is the reason, that for AR(\(p\)), first \(p\) residuals are NA.

If the model chosen is fitting the data adequately, \(\hat e_t\) should behave like \(e_t\). i.e. residuals should behave like White Noise.

Plot ACF and PACF of the residuals, and look for sign of non-WN.

Ex: Residual Analysis

  set.seed(3563)
  Y    <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, .3) ), 100 )
  plot(Y, type="o")

  Fit09 <- Arima(Y, order=c(2,0,0), include.mean=FALSE)          # fit AR(2)
  Fit09

4. Ex: Dow Jones 1972

  # read in daily Dow Jones data from my website
  D  <- read.csv("https://nmimoto.github.io/datasets/dowj.csv")
  D1 <- ts(D, start=c(1972,1), freq=12)   # turn the data into TS object
  plot(D1)

  Y <- diff(log(D1))                  # Take log-difference

Summary

  • To fit AR(p), you must choose with mean or without mean. It is controled by include.mean=TRUE/FALSE option in Arima or auto.arima.

  • Look at sample ACF and sample PACF to guess p.

  • Use minumum Akaike Information Criteria (AIC) criteria to look for the best \(p\).

  • Check parameter significance of estimated parameters.

  • After getting the suggested “best” \(p\) from AIC, fit model with p+1, and check to see if the last parameter estimate comes out non-significant.

  • Check residuals for randomness (no-autocorrelation) by plotting reiduals itself, and its ACF and PACF.
